Senior at USC; one summer she chose to take Algebra 1 during the summer at the local public school as a refresher before she started Honors Algebra 2. She was dismayed at how the teachers spoke to the students and expected the students to fail in life.  A daily comment by the teacher was &quot;For those very few of you who will actually attempt any schooling after High School....&quot;  At my daughter's private high school the sentence was &quot;When you are in college or at a university.....&quot;  It was expected that every student would attend a higher education institute.   The public schools in our area are horribly staffed, under supplied and the classes are huge.  45 kids per class, in relation to the 23 kids that make up the entire 6th grade at my youngest daughters school.  A school that allows her to grow and excel, she goes to the 7th grade for math and reading.  What public school allows that? "/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="1206" language="en" documentId="3169" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="Shelli Jenkins" date="Aug 29, 2013 7:37PM" docType="artcomment" origUrl="http://living.msn.com/family-parenting/the-family-room-blog-post?post=ab228ffc-1e99-4b37-a7b8-0b6a4c3fb240" topic="public-private-schools" thumbsUp="13" thumbsDown="0" origId="3169" notes="" title="Is it wrong to send kids to private school?"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="1206"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39"/></xmi:XMI>